		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/12/11/verizon-says-investment-will-be-unaffected-by-net-neutrality-policy/" data-title="Verizon Says Investment Will Be Unaffected by Net Neutrality Policy" data-description="Francis J. Shammo, Verizon&#039;s chief financial officer, said the company planned to continue to invest in its FiOS fiber-optic network and its wireless systems regardless of the outcome of the broadband debate.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w315"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/11/technology/11bits-verizon/11bits-verizon-master315.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/11/technology/11bits-verizon/11bits-verizon-master315.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/11/technology/11bits-verizon/11bits-verizon-master315.jpg" id="100000003298994" width="315" height="210" alt="Verizon said it planned to continue investing in its FiOS fiber-optic network and its wireless systems regardless of the outcome of the broadband debate."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="210"><meta itemprop="width" content="315"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Verizon said it planned to continue investing in its FiOS fiber-optic network and its wireless systems regardless of the outcome of the broadband debate.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> John Minchillo/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A senior executive of Verizon, which successfully challenged the Federal Communications Commissionâs 2010 net neutrality rules in federal court, said Tuesday that the companyâs plans for future investment in its networks would not be affected even if the F.C.C. decides to begin regulating Internet access as a utility.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Francis J. Shammo, Verizon&#8217;s chief financial officer, said at the annual UBS media and communications investment conference that the company planned to continue to invest in its FiOS fiber-optic network and its wireless systems regardless of the outcome of the broadband debate.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI mean to be real clear, I mean this does not influence the way we invest,â Mr. Shammo said, according to a <a href="//seekingalpha.com/article/2743375-verizon-communications-vz-presents-at-ubs-42nd-annual-global-media-and-communications-conference-transcript?part=single" title="Transcript of meeting.">transcript</a> of the meeting. âI mean we&#8217;re going to continue to invest in our networks and our platforms, both in wireless and wireline FiOS and where we need to. So nothing will influence that.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Shammo said Verizon believed that the F.C.C. had enough authority already to enforce net neutrality without taking the âextremeâ step of classifying broadband access as a utility under Title II of the Communications Act. And he warned that if the F.C.C. chose to classify broadband as a utility, the policy would be tied up in litigation for years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The debate has heated up since President Obama urged the F.C.C. last month to adopt a Title II regulatory regime to guarantee that Internet service providers cannot block or discriminate against legal online content.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Opponents have said that such a move will stifle investment by companies. This week, a group of large telecommunications equipment companies, including Cisco Systems, IBM and Intel, wrote to the F.C.C. urging it not to adopt Title II classification.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âTitle II would lead to a slowdown, if not a hold, in broadband build-out, because if you donât know that you can recover on your investment, you wonât make it,â the group wrote <a href="//www.tiaonline.org/sites/default/files/pages/Internet_ecosystem_letter_FINAL_12.10.14.pdf" title="The letter from Title II opponents.">in its letter</a>. âThe investment shortfall would then flow downstream, landing first and squarely on technology companies like ours, and then working its way through the economy over all. Just a few years removed from the worst recession in memory, thatâs a risk no policy maker should accept, let alone promote.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But there is evidence that some of those concerns might be overblown. Verizon is believed to be one of the companies bidding aggressively for new airwaves for mobile broadband that are now being auctioned by the F.C.C. Those auctions have already bid up prices for the available airwaves, or spectrum, to more than $40 billion, four times the original minimum set by the F.C.C. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Commission officials and others have said that the success of the auction disproves the assertion that even the threat of Title II regulation will stifle investment.</p>
	</div>
